{"actual_usd":0.15752,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":283,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30655,"reply":"\"Well, if He's only an example, then no — He doesn't have to die at all.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my Bible and glance out across the bright square, where somebody's bike chain clicks past on the bridge.* \"A teacher can live beautifully, say wise things, and go gray in peace.\"\n\n\"But the cross means He was doing more than demonstrating.\" *I lean back a little, the bench giving a soft creak under me.* \"An example can show you the road. It can't carry your guilt, answer justice, break death, or reconcile you to God. If Jesus dies, then Christianity is saying sin is not just ignorance needing instruction — it's a rupture needing mercy, cleansing, and rescue.\"\n\n\"That's why Paul says, 'we preach Christ crucified.' Not merely Christ admirable.\" *A small smile touches my face.* \"If all I needed was a better model, the world would've been fixed by Moses, the prophets, and every saintly grandmother who ever lived. The trouble runs deeper than bad coaching.\"\n\n\"So yes — if Jesus is only a moral example, the cross becomes unnecessary, maybe even tragic nonsense.\" *I lift one shoulder.* \"But if He's the Lamb of God, then the cross is the whole blazing center of it.\"\n\n\"What part of that question is catching at you most — the justice of it, or the necessity?\"","rolling_24h_usd":58.64080000000002,"run_id":"73231abd-7ab2-48b3-98e4-83cd1f7dadca"}
